<br>
Sorry to hear it didn't work any better this time than last, Alianna.  I can't say I'm particularly surprised, but it's still a bummer.  I, personally, have been playing EQ lately (yeah, I know, anyone who feels compelled to flame has an open invitation to kiss my ass) and having a lot of fun with it.  The fun factor is largely due to the fact that I play with an RL friend (who I might be trying out DAoC with later, since he seems to be interested in it, and I'm highly suggestible).  Other than that, I'm burning time with Sir-Tech's Wizardry 8 (which everyone should own.  this is what games are about.) and Star Trek: Armada 2.  Given the stability of the games I've just mentioned, AO looks that much worse in comparison.<br>
<br>
And to Bjond:  Here's the hardware setup I had while playing AO:<br>
<br>
1 GHz Pentium 3 CPU<br>
Asus CuBX board, FSB overclocked to 133 MHz<br>
512 MB Micron PC133 SDRAM<br>
Hercules Geforce 2 MX<br>
Sound Blaster Live! Value<br>
Western Digital 20 GB ATA 100 HDD<br>
3Com Etherlink 10/100 NIC<br>
Windows 2000 SP 2 (not hardware, but important)<br>
<br>
The rest (CD-ROM, burner, misc. cooling) really isn't relevant.  But, to my mind, this is pretty damn tuned up hardware.  While I didn't see all the problems people complained about, and my lag wasn't too bad (cable modem) most of the time, the game was still inexcusably buggy and crash-prone.  My system DOES NOT CRASH playing anything other than AO.  But in AO, when I zoned, I had probably a 50/50 shot of still being logged in when I hit the other side.  And that was the least irritating bug.<br>
<br>
So, no, it doesn't just take a lot of tuning to play AO.  It takes obscene amounts of luck as well, and even at that, it's still not a smooth ride. <p>~Jaqrabbit<br>
